Certainly! Below is a simple HTML file that creates a 3D animation of the number "1" spinning around. The code includes embedded CSS and JavaScript, all within a single code block. You can copy and paste this code into an HTML file and open it in a web browser to see the animation.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>3D Spinning Number 1</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #282c34;
            perspective: 1000px;
        }

        .number {
            font-size: 100px;
            color: #61dafb;
            transform-style: preserve-3d;
            animation: spin 5s linear infinite;
        }

        @keyframes spin {
            from {
                transform: rotateY(0deg);
            }
            to {
                transform: rotateY(360deg);
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="number">1</div>

    <script>
        // You can add any additional JavaScript here if needed
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Copy the code above.
2. Open a text editor (like Notepad, VSCode, or any code editor).
3. Paste the code into the editor.
4. Save the file with a `.html` extension, for example, `spinning_number.html`.
5. Open the saved file in a web browser.

You should see the number "1" spinning in 3D!

Certainly! Below is an example of a simple web app that uses Three.js to create a 3D spinning number "1". The code is all contained within a single HTML file, including embedded CSS and JavaScript.

Make sure you have an internet connection when you run this, as it loads the Three.js library from a CDN.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>3D Spinning Number 1</title>
    <style>
        body {
            margin: 0;
            overflow: hidden;
            background-color: #282c34;
        }
        canvas {
            display: block;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/three.js/r128/three.min.js"></script>
    <script>
        // Scene setup
        const scene = new THREE.Scene();
        const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
        const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer();
        renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);

        // Create a 3D text geometry
        const loader = new THREE.FontLoader();
        loader.load('https://threejs.org/fonts/helvetiker_regular.typeface.json', function (font) {
            const geometry = new THREE.TextGeometry('1', {
                font: font,
                size: 1,
                height: 0.2,
                curveSegments: 12,
                bevelEnabled: true,
                bevelThickness: 0.03,
                bevelSize: 0.05,
                bevelOffset: 0,
                bevelSegments: 5
            });

            const material = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial({ color: 0x61dafb });
            const textMesh = new THREE.Mesh(geometry, material);
            scene.add(textMesh);

            // Position the text
            textMesh.position.set(-0.5, 0, -3);

            // Animation loop
            const animate = function () {
                requestAnimationFrame(animate);
                textMesh.rotation.y += 0.01; // Spin the text
                renderer.render(scene, camera);
            };

            animate();
        });

        // Camera position
        camera.position.z = 5;

        // Handle window resize
        window.addEventListener('resize', () => {
            camera.aspect = window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight;
            camera.updateProjectionMatrix();
            renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Copy the code above.
2. Open a text editor (like Notepad, VSCode, or any code editor).
3. Paste the code into the editor.
4. Save the file with a `.html` extension, for example, `3d_spinning_number.html`.
5. Open the saved file in a web browser.

You should see a 3D number "1" spinning in the center of the screen! Make sure you have an internet connection to load the Three.js library and the font.
